<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Hoverspeed gets duty-free licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hoverspeed, the cross-channel hovercraft operator, yesterday received a
licence for its duty-free shop at Dover - 18 years after it first opened,
Neil Buckley writes.
Bemused magistrates at Dover granted the Pounds 12.50 licence for selling
wines, spirits and beer after it emerged that due to an oversight the shop
had been operating illegally since it was opened by Hover-speed's
predecessor company Seaspeed.
The company does not require a licence for duty-free sales on cross-channel
hovercraft and SeaCat vessels, but had omitted to apply for one for its
on-shore shop. The mistake was discovered last month when police checked
their records after an application by Hoverspeed's new competitor
Eurotunnel, operator of the Channel tunnel, for a licence to run a duty-free
shop at nearby Folkestone.
Mrs Vivien Judd, a Dover magistrate, criticised police and asked for a
written report on why the company was allowed to continue trading after the
mistake was discovered.
Mr James Rankin, for Hoverspeed, apologised to magistrates for the lateness
of the application 'which should have been made 18 years ago'.
</TEXT>
