<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / French blamed for conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria accused France yesterday of escalating Nigeria's border conflict
with Cameroon by sending paratroopers there.
'It is a direct provocation and we regard the escalation of the conflict as
the entire responsibility of the French,' Mr Baba Gana Kingibe, foreign
minister, told a news conference.
A contingent of 15 French paratroopers and two helicopters arrived in
Yaounde on Sunday after Nigerian and Cameroonian troops exchanged fire in
the oil-rich Bakassi peninsula which both west African countries claim.
'I hope that war is not imminent. Our endeavour is to avoid war. . . . but
that does not preclude our being prepared for any provocation from France or
Cameroon,' said Mr Kingibe.
French companies have close ties with the Nigeria in the oil industry,
manufacturing and construction. Elf Aquitaine owns 40 per cent of a joint
venture with the Nigerian government producing 100,000 barrels a day of
crude oil.
Elf is also in partnership with Shell, Agip and the Nigerian government in
the Dollars 4bn liquefied natural gas project re-launched this year.
</TEXT>
