FT  03 MAR 94 / Clinton urged to back jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International trade union leaders will tomorrow urge President Bill Clinton
to back a 'global new deal' to create jobs for the estimated 35m unemployed
in western industrialised countries.
Led by Mr Lane Kirkland, head of the American AFL-CIO, OECD union officials
will demand 'a profound change in the direction of international economic
policy' at the G7 jobs summit in Detroit later this month.
Union leaders will urge Mr Robert Reich, US labour secretary, to back their
call for a co-ordinated employment growth strategy and reject current
western economic policies. They want cuts in short-term interest rates in
Europe; a growth strategy based on infrastructure investments; regional
development; targeted research spending; the encouragement of small and
medium-sized enterprises.
