<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Federation may unleash violence, say Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Serb leaders yesterday warned that the preliminary agreement to form a
federation reached by Bosnia's Croats and Moslems in Washington could
unleash a new wave of violence in former Yugoslavia.
They suggested the US was restoring the Moslem-Croat coalition to step up
pressure on the Serbs and stressed the key question of territorial division
among the three sides remained unresolved.
Bosnia's prime minister, Mr Haris Silajdzic, said yesterday that he planned
to meet Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russian foreign minister, in Moscow this week to
seek Russia's help in ending the fighting. 'We want the leadership of the US
to continue but the Russian role is important when it comes to Serbs,' he
said.
Meanwhile, Bosnian Serb artillery pounded the Moslem enclave of Maglaj in
northern Bosnia where 19,000 refugees have been under siege for most of the
past year, and pressed an offensive against the north-western Bihac pocket.
UN officials also said Serbs fired on the government town of Breza north of
Sarajevo, while rocket-propelled grenades were aimed at Bosnian positions in
the capital.
In Moscow, Mr Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of the Bosnian Serb assembly who is
there with the Bosnian Serb leadership, said the Washington agreement was
seen as 'an action against the Serbian people. It is incomprehensible to
form such an artificial creation which cannot last. . . . (and) aims to
isolate Serbs.'
Mr Radovan Karadzic, Bosnian Serb leader, told a news conference in Moscow:
'We welcome this agreement if America helps Moslems and Croats move towards
peace. But if it helps them to put pressure on Serbs and to gain more
territory from them we are against it.'
But the leadership in Belgrade appeared more restrained. Mr Vladislav
Jovanovic, Serbian foreign minister, said that Serbia supported 'every
attempt to stop the war' but warned that the US initiative for Bosnian
Croats and Moslems to form a federation and then join Croatia in a
confederation could lead to a 'further escalation of crisis'.
By contrast, President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia welcomed the agreement
'which paved the way for resolving Croatia's troubles, but most of all the
UNPA zones' (Serb-held areas of Croatia under United Nations supervision).
However, UN officials yesterday said Mr Tudjman had not given up his plans
of creating a Greater Croatia incorporating large parts of northern, central
and western Bosnia-Hercegovina.
Croatian officials say that the US promised to back the return of the UN
zones, part of the self-styled Serb state of Krajina, to Zagreb. But Serb
leaders from Krajina, which covers one-third of Croatia, denounced the
agreement as 'totally unacceptable'.
Extra UK troops row, Page 8
</TEXT>
