<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Price-protest miners vote to stay out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Australian coalminers, on strike since Sunday to protest at lower coal
export prices, have voted to stay out until Friday, Reuter reports from
Sydney. Those attending a rally in Canberra demanded an inquiry into
negotiations between Australian coal companies and Japanese buyers.
A deal covering Australian coking coal reached in January resulted in price
cuts of 8-9.5 per cent for the year starting April 1. The miners, who say
the cuts will lead to fewer jobs and mine closures, repeated their demand
for a national coal-marketing authority to negotiate prices with Japanese
buyers. Companies say that would be tantamount to nationalisation.
The miners vowed to strike indefinitely if employers took disciplinary
action. Mr John Maitland, miners' union president, will meet Prime Minister
Paul Keating today to discuss the miners' case.
