<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / World Stock Markets: Brazil ends a net 1.8% up, Mexico down
2.8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil
Brazilian equities closed a net 1.8 per cent higher in moderate trade after
the market absorbed a late profit-taking bout and remained bullish on
economy minister Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso's anti-inflation plan,
including the creation of a new single price index.
The Bovespa index of the 54 most active shares gained 194 points at 10,733
in Sao Paulo. Volume ended at Cr216.8bn (Dollars 335m).
Traders said investors sold on concern that congress would not muster quorum
to approve the promulgation of a bill creating Mr Cardoso's social welfare
fund. But a congressional spokesman said shortly after the market closed
that congress had reached minimum quorum to proceed with the vote.
Brazil's central bank will use the newly created single price index, Real
Value Unit, as a parameter for its interventions in the foreign exchange
market, Reuter reports from Sao Paulo.
The bank said it will sell US dollars in the commercial and the interbank
domestic forex markets at the URV price of the day the deal takes place.
The rate at which the central bank will buy dollars in the market will be
set freely between market players and the monetary authority. The deals will
be settled two days after the transaction takes place.
The URV's value will be set daily, based on the average of three inflation
indices which measure the depreciation of the cruzeiro real and expressed in
dollars.
Mexico
Mexican stock prices tumbled more than 70 points to close sharply lower, hit
by fears of a rise in domestic interest rates and losses on Wall Street.
The IPC index of 36 leading shares ended 71.29 down at 2,514.15, a loss of
2.76 per cent.
Telmex accounted for about half of the total of 90.23m shares traded. The
'A' stock dropped 3.15 per cent and the 'L' shares, which may be held by
foreigners, lost 2.60 per cent.
Of 115 issues changing hands on the wider market, falls outpaced rises by 78
to 15.
