<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / International Company News: Blockbuster shareholders' Viacom
move rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A Delaware court yesterday rejected a move to block a Dollars 1.25bn
investment by Blockbuster Entertainment, the US home video company, in cable
television group Viacom.
The application had been brought by some shareholders in Blockbuster, which
had agreed to pay Dollars 55 a share for a stake in Viacom to provide cash
for the cable TV company's winning bid for Paramount Communications.
Viacom's non-voting 'B' shares were trading yesterday at Dollars 29.
The Delaware chancery court said blocking the investment would case
'enormous uncertainty with widespread repercussions, causing Paramount
Communications stockholders to reconsider their decision to tender their
shares under Viacom's tender offer'.
Blockbuster shareholders have yet to vote on whether to accept an all-share
offer for the company from Viacom. Although it has already received the
backing of Blockbuster's board, the deal has come under fire from some
shareholders given the sharp fall in Viacom's share price.
