<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / International Company News: Deficit deepens at Nissan
Spanish unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Expectations of sharply deteriorating results at Nissan Motor Iberica, the
Spanish subsidiary of the Japanese Nissan car group, were confirmed
yesterday with the announcement of a Pta40.95bn (Dollars 293m) pre-tax loss
for 1993. This was almost three times its deficit of Pta14.37bn the previous
year.
The figures were in line with forecasts.
They reflected a rise in net operating losses, to Pta23.21bn from Pta8.26bn,
and higher financial costs of Pta21.17bn compared with Pta11.10bn.
However the year showed an increase in sales by the company, which makes
commercial and four-wheel drive vehicles, to Pta182bn from Pta163bn. Unit
sales rose by about 3,500 to just over 100,000.
Last November, Nissan increased its stake in the company from 70 per cent to
96 per cent at a cost of about Pta8.5bn. It also announced a three-year
restructuring plan, including the laying off of 1,000 of its 7,000
employees.
Nissan's difficulties in Spain, where it has five plants, have coincided
with problems at Volkswagen's Seat subsidiary and Suzuki's offshoot, Santana
Motor, which filed for receivership earlier last month and is seeking
government support.
