<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / International Company News: Low newsprint prices keep
Abitibi in red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Low paper prices drove Abitibi-Price, the world's biggest newsprint
producer, to its fourth consecutive year of losses in 1993, writes Bernard
Simon.
The Toronto-based company said newsprint prices in North America had shown
no signs of recovery this year.
However, it was counting on a combination of higher offshore prices, a 7 per
cent cut in North American discounts, and price rise to lift operating
results during 1994.
Net losses last year totalled CDollars 121.7m (USDollars 90.1m), or CDollars
1.71 a share, a significant improvement on 1992's CDollars 220.9m deficit,
equal to CDollars 3.19 a share. The results include a narrowing in losses
from discontinued operations, to CDollars 13.4m from CDollars 27.8m.
Sales rose to CDollars 1.87bn from CDollars 1.60bn while operating losses
fell to CDollars 39.8m from CDollars 138.1m.
