<DATE>940302
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Dawson to make Pounds 50m provision for US
shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dawson International, the Edinburgh-based textile group, is closing its
fleece and jersey business in the US and taking a Pounds 50m exceptional
provision for the year to March 26 1994.
The rationalisation was announced yesterday following an independent review
of Dawson's US businesses, which had sales of Pounds 214m in 1992-93, about
half the group total.
Last month the shares fell to 134p after the group warned that difficult US
trading conditions would lead to 'a very substantial exceptional provision
this year.'
Yesterday they closed down 5p at 153p.
Dawson is also considering the sale of Dawson Home Fashions, which makes
shower curtains and bath mats.
Although it had 60 per cent of the US market last year, DHF has been hit
badly by import penetration. Operating profits in the six months to
September 25 amounted to just Pounds 300,000 on turnover of Pounds 30.4m.
The fleece and jersey business lost Pounds 8.9m on sales of Pounds 29.1m in
the same period. Known as JE Morgan Apparel, it operates 12 plants and has
2,000 employees.
Sir Ronald Miller, executive chairman, said the three plants making fleece,
which is used in jogging suits, would be closed.
Three of the remaining plants are dedicated to making jersey, which is used
for T-shirts and underwear.
These would be reorganised, along with the jersey-making operations of the
mixed plants, with a view to a possible sale.
Dawson went into the jersey and fleece business in 1989, and was a supplier
to Kmart, the US retailing group. Sir Ronald said the business had been hit
by excess capacity in the US, imports, lower sales in the recession and the
battle between US retailers. He pointed out that Kmart lost Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 600m) in the fourth quarter.
Goodwill of Pounds 42m from the purchase of JE Morgan will need to be
written off through the profit and loss account.
A further Pounds 14m will need to be written off if the shower curtain
business is sold.
The group's net debt at March 26 is expected to be about Pounds 70m.
It also has Pounds 27.9m of convertible preference shares.
Dawson has two further businesses in the US, Morgan and Duofold, which make
thermal underwear and other clothing. The group expects this year's results
to be better than last year's.
Sir Ronald said the rationalisation would enable the company to concentrate
on its profitable US operations.
</TEXT>
