<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Salomon to advise on UK debt sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK Treasury has appointed Salomon Brothers International to advise on
disposals of its remaining holdings of debt in privatised UK companies in
the next financial year.
It is the first time that Salomon Brothers has been awarded a senior role by
the UK Treasury since it was ditched from the BT2 privatisation, after being
involved in a US Treasury auction scandal in 1991.
The Treasury said it had taken the unusual step of appointing a non-UK bank
because Salomon 'gave us the best presentation'.
The Treasury sold Pounds 1.3bn of similar debt in 1992 through a complex
auction, arranged by Barings, in which 13 privatised companies were invited
to bid to buy back their debt. Outside investors were allowed to compete for
BT debt.
The government still holds a total of Pounds 2.86bn of the debt - Pounds
1.22bn of BT debt and Pounds 1.64bn of electricity debt - which was left on
the companies' balance sheets at the time of privatisation. However, some of
that debt is very short-dated and unlikely to be sold.
Salomon will advise the Treasury on which and how much debt to sell, and how
to sell it.
The government aims to raise Pounds 5.5bn in privatisation proceeds in the
next financial year. The debt sale will allow greater leeway in the timing
of further electricity offerings.
However, one difficulty in selling the debt is that, with coupons of more
than 12 per cent - much higher than current market yields - it would have to
be priced at a premium of around 30 per cent above its notional value, which
could make it unattractive to potential buyers.
</TEXT>
