<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Croats and Moslems sign pact: Bosnian Serbs agree to open
Tuzla airport for relief flights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Moslems and Croats reached agreement last night after four days of
talks in Washington on plans for a loose federation of the two ethnic groups
in the war-torn republic.
The breakthrough came on the same day as Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian
foreign minister, managed to persuade Mr Radovan Karadzic, leader of the
Bosnian Serbs who is on a visit to Moscow, to allow Tuzla airport to be
placed under UN supervision, making it easier to transport aid.
In Washington, the Bosnian Moslem-Croat federation was established in a
framework deal, which included an outline agreement for a confederation
between it and neighbouring Croatia.
The accord, signed by Mr Mate Granic, the Croatian foreign minister, Mr
Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian prime minister, and Mr Kresimir Zubak, leader
of the Bosnian Croats, creates a federation of cantons with a central
government responsible for foreign affairs, national defence and commerce.
The president and vice-president will be elected by a two-house legislature
with the two ethnic groups alternating yearly in holding the positions.
The cantons will have authority over police, education, culture, housing,
public services and radio and television. All refugees and displaced people
will be guaranteed the right to return to their homes or to be compensated.
A deadline of March 15 was set for drafting a constitution for the new state
and for completing work on the confederation.
While the accord - which leaves details such as military issues still to be
resolved - does not address the Serb-held areas of Bosnia, US officials hope
it will put further pressure on the Serbs to make peace.
The US has offered both carrot and stick to Croatia as an inducement to end
the fighting between Croats and Moslems in central Bosnia. While threatening
economic sanctions on Croatia, officials have also held out the hope of
loans from international financial institutions.
In Moscow, Mr Kozyrev hailed the agreement with Mr Karadzic as a 'big step'
in a Russian peace initiative launched when President Boris Yeltsin
persuaded the Serbs to heed the Nato ultimatum for pulling back heavy
artillery from around Sarajevo.
After the accord, Russia said: 'This position of the Bosnian Serbs is based
on the fact that Russian observers will take part in monitoring the
non-military use of (Tuzla) airport.'
However, Mr Karadzic admitted the talks had been difficult.
The momentum for peace is being reflected on the ground, although with
varying degrees of success. Yesterday the International Red Cross secured
the release of 400 prisoners in the western city of Mostar, which had been
besieged by Croats for several months.
The UN High Commissioner for Refugees also resumed aid convoys and
humanitarian flights into the Bosnian capital Sarajevo.
'New primitives' drive Serb professionals abroad, Page 2
</TEXT>
