<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Rule change urged for ITV groups: Ownership regime
'restrictive'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission has come out in favour of a
fundamental reform of commercial television ownership rules to ease
restrictions on takeovers and allow newspapers to have larger stakes in
broadcasters.
In its submission to Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary who is
reviewing cross-media ownership regulations, the ITC says the present rules
are too restrictive.
In particular, the quality of ITV service could suffer unless something is
done about the disparity between large and small ITV groups.
The commission believes that the main terrestrial channels will continue to
dominate UK viewing into the next century. But as the number of cable and
satellite channels grows there is less justification for restrictions on
changes in ownership 'designed originally to cater for broadcasting services
in fixed overall supply'.
The best way to protect diversity of information sources while allowing
small regional ITV companies to be part of larger groups is to set a
market-share limit for ITV ownership rather than restricting ownership to
the present maximum two licences.
The ITC believes the ceiling should be set at 25 per cent of television
advertising revenue with no limit on licences.
The commission thinks newspaper groups should be able to take stakes in
broadcasters, short of control. This is defined as 30 per cent, compared
with the present 20 per cent. The ITC concludes this would be 'an
appropriate first step, to be reviewed for its effectiveness'.
ITV companies should be able to take stakes of up to 30 per cent in the
planned Channel 5 instead of 20 per cent.
The commission also attacks the government stipulation that the ITV
companies should hold less than 50 per cent of Independent Television News
by the end of this year. This 'lacks solid justification' and there is no
leading network in other parts of the world which is not able to control the
main source of its national and international news.
The ITC suggests that as satellite viewing increases there could come a
point when the cross-media restrictions which apply to terrestrial services
should also be applied to satellite services.
British Sky Broadcasting, in which Mr Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation has
a 50 per cent stake and Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, is a
significant shareholder, is not subject to cross-media rules.
The possibility of undesirable dominance occurring through 'agenda setting'
means that restrictions on ownership should continue.
The ITC believes the government should define in terms of ownership or
revenue share when ownership restrictions should apply to the new cable and
satellite services.
</TEXT>
