<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Invasion of privacy to be criminal offence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has decided to push ahead with new criminal offences covering
electronic eavesdropping and the use of long-range photography on private
property.
The offences, which will apply to everyone and not only the media, will be a
key part of a white paper on privacy expected to be published later this
month.
The offences, first suggested by the Calcutt committee on the press and
privacy, have been tacitly accepted by large sections of the press providing
they are not specifically aimed at the media and there will be a possible
defence of public interest.
The government seems to be increasingly wary of creating a right for
citizens to sue for breaches of privacy.
Apart from problems of definition, ministers such as Mr Peter Brooke, the
national heritage secretary, are understood to be concerned that without
legal aid - and the pressures on the legal aid system are already
considerable - only the rich would be able to protect their privacy.
The possibility of a civil tort of privacy will, it is believed, be retained
in the white paper as will the suggestion that there could be a statutory
ombudsman as a 'court of appeal' over the Press Complaints Commission, the
industry's self-regulating body.
The two proposed measures in the white paper are seen largely as a stick to
encourage the press to continue strengthening self-regulation.
There is little enthusiasm in the government for a statutory ombudsman, and
Lord McGregor, chairman of the commission, as well as other commission
members, have said they will resign if an ombudsman is imposed.
In November, after unauthorised pictures of the Princess of Wales were
printed in the Sunday and Daily Mirror, Mr Brooke warned, that the press had
to demonstrate that it could respect and abide by its own rules.
The appointment of Professor Robert Pinker, a PCC member, as privacy
commissioner to head investigations into unnecessary invasions of privacy
was seen as a step in the right direction.
It may decide to make the privacy commissioner more independent of the
complaints commission in return for dropping the proposals of a civil tort
and a statutory ombudsman.
</TEXT>
