<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Rebel Tory peers hail police bill climbdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rebel Conservative peers yesterday welcomed a climbdown on police reform by
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, removing the threat of a damaging defeat
in the Lords.
Mr Howard was forced to abandon the key elements of his proposals to remove
police authorities from the control of local councillors.
The climbdown is an embarrassment to Mr Howard, who faces criticism of the
criminal justice bill, the other important law-and-order measure announced
in the autumn. It is a further blow to Mr John Major's Back to Basics
campaign for traditional values, in which a crackdown on law and order is
prominent.
Lord Whitelaw, the former Conservative deputy prime minister who led
opposition to key elements, said the changes to the bill were 'of enormous
importance to our country'.
Lord Callaghan, former Labour prime minister, said the government had 'given
up the substance and kept the form' of the bill to avoid defeat. Lord
Jenkins of Hillhead, the former Labour home secretary who is now a Liberal
Democrat, said Mr Howard had 'mixed dogma and hubris with a reluctance to
consult and a determination to legislate at almost any price'.
The climbdown was announced by Earl Ferrers, the Home Office minister,
before the Lords resumed a line-by-line debate on the police and criminal
evidence bill.
He said the government would drop plans to remove the automatic majority
enjoyed by local authorities on police authorities, which at present consist
of two-thirds councillors and one-third magistrates.
He said most police authorities would have nine councillors, five Home
Office nominees and three magistrates.
The Home Office nominees will be chosen by selection panels consisting of
one member chosen by the home secretary, one chosen by councillors and
magistrates, and one chosen jointly.
The selection panels will produce a list of candidates from which the home
secretary will nominate five.
</TEXT>
