<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Scottish Office to amend bill
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Office intends to amend the bill to reform local government,
now going through parliament, to enable Strathclyde Regional Council to
conclude a deal to lease Pounds 36m of trains for its passenger transport
executive.
The leasing of the trains, to be built by Hunslett TPL of Leeds, has been
held up since last autumn because Lombard North Central, the leasing
company, said there was inadequate security because Strathclyde is to be
broken into 10 councils under the reform.
The Scottish Office says it will seek to amend the legislation to permit the
council to lease the trains. Strathclyde believes a legally binding letter
stating this intention will be enough to unblock the deal. It says the
diesel multiple units should go into service by mid-1996.
Mr Malcolm Waugh, chairman of Strathclyde Regional Council's transport
committee, welcomed what he called a volte face by Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton, the Scottish Office minister.
He said, however, that the council would receive the trains 10 months later
than it might have done if Lord James had accepted what the council said in
the first place.
</TEXT>
