<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Minister dismisses wider aid-for-arms allegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allegations that Britain's overseas aid programme was linked to arms deals
with several countries were dismissed as 'absolute nonsense' by Mr Alastair
Goodlad, Foreign Office minister of state, last night.
He told the Commons that its foreign affairs committee should be left to
deal with claims that a contract to sell Pounds 1bn of arms to Malaysia was
won because the UK gave Pounds 234m aid for building the Pergau
hydro-electric dam.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, is due to give evidence to the committee
today.
Sir David Steel, foreign affairs spokesman for the Liberal Democrats,
highlighted the role of Baroness Thatcher, when prime minister, in seeking
to expand British trade with Malaysia.
He said her 'close circle' had been involved. 'In this case Sir Tim Bell,
well known as her public relations adviser, is also adviser to the Malaysian
prime minister and to Tan Sri Armugam, who controls GEC Malaysia, heavily
involved in several of the contracts under the deal.'
A Liberal Democrat motion asserting that the Pergau dam allegations had
'seriously undermined the credibility of the British aid programme' was
defeated by a government majority of 146 (305-159).
Mr Goodlad also condemned suggestions that British companies which
contributed to Conservative party funds had been the main beneficiaries of
contracts arising from overseas aid and trade deals.
Mr Tom Clarke, shadow minister for overseas aid, accused Mr Goodlad of
attempting to deal with the Pergau dam issue almost as an aside.
Mr Richard Needham, the trade minister, said only 1.2 per cent of the aid
budget would be allocated to the dam in any single year.
He warned that the 'distortions of some sections of the press' and the
attacks made by opposition MPs on Malaysia, Indonesia and Thailand could put
jobs at risk.
</TEXT>
