<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Reforms at TUC win wide backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, was joined by other political parties,
employers' organisations and industry leaders in welcoming the Trades Union
Congress's announcement yesterday of a 'relaunch' of its aims.
The TUC said it wanted to broaden its links and exert influence across the
political spectrum and not just inside the Labour party.
Mr Hunt said he saw the modernisation as 'a welcome and necessary step if
unions are to market their services to their individual members more
effectively in the workplace and help employers to become more competitive'.
Mr John Smith, Labour leader, acknowledged that 'the TUC . . . should have
the widest possible influence'.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, said the congress wanted to 'signal
that we want to work as partners with employers who will work with us to
maximise job and income security'.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the CBI, said he believed the new
approach would 'help to develop even better understanding between employers
and unions'.
Sir Denys Henderson, chairman of ICI, said: 'It is important the TUC should
be able to function efficiently and effectively.'
