<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Chambers attack insolvency laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conflicts of interest which could arise when accountants investigating
companies are then appointed as its receivers should be examined by the
government, says the British Chambers of Commerce.
The government should also consider the scope for establishing an
independent watchdog to protect creditors' rights and oversee the sale of
any assets by receivers back to the directors of an insolvent company.
A document prepared by the Mid-Yorkshire Chamber of Commerce and Industry,
which is to be circulated to other member bodies across the country today,
is the latest in a series of attacks on insolvency law.
It substantially extends the scope of reform proposed in a consultative
report issued by the Department of Trade and Industry last year. The DTI
suggested reforms to Company Voluntary Arrangements, an insolvency procedure
introduced in 1986 and widely criticised for its lack of effectiveness.
Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the British chambers, said:
'Insolvency law is not something people lie dreaming about, but we have
identified what we believe to be some quite serious flaws in legislation.'
The chambers' document is expected to call for discussion of whether there
should be a clearer division of roles when banks which appoint accountants
to investigate the affairs of a company also appoint that firm as receivers.
It stresses that it has not discovered any evidence of accountants
recommending that a business be put into insolvency to generate more work.
It argues, however, that there is conflict between the interests of the bank
or other secured creditors and the interests of other creditors and
management.
It says there is concern among creditors about the sale of assets back to
directors of insolvent companies. There is also concern for greater
vigilance of fraud.
The document argues for greater flexibility by government collection
agencies such as the Inland Revenue, which are often the creditors that
trigger company insolvencies because they have little discretion to make
com-mercial judgments about a company.
In line with a highly critical report from the National Audit Office last
year, it urges the DTI to actively prosecute, disqualify and debar directors
where there are concerns about their conduct.
It calls for simplification of administration, another procedure introduced
in 1986. It says the courts should be bypassed and the decision of whether
to grant an administration order handed to insolvency practitioners.
It also argues for modifications to company voluntary arrangements so that
they are no longer linked to administration orders.
</TEXT>
