<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / N-waste delays pose threat to safety'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Workers handling radioactive waste at sites owned by the Atomic Energy
Authority could suffer additional doses of radiation because of delays in
constructing a permanent repository for nuclear waste in the UK, a nuclear
safety study group said yesterday.
The group, set up by the Health and Safety Executive's nuclear safety
committee, said the sites were running out of storage space.
The group's report, however, concludes that the authority is aware of these
problems and is dealing with them. The authority said it accepted the
findings, and was addressing the specific problems identified.
The report says that at Sellafield in Cumbria there are still serious
problems left over from a fire in 1952. At Dounreay in the Highlands, where
the prototype of a fast breeder reactor is being decommissioned, waste
storage is 'very much of a hand-to-mouth existence'.
It also says the delay in the repository programme and in a new agreement on
packaging specifications for nuclear waste were preventing the more secure
storage of waste.
Yesterday's findings do not directly affect plans to privatise the Atomic
Energy Authority. The division responsible for managing and decommissioning
redundant plant will remain in government hands.
