<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Attorney-general fights pressure to resign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, IVOR OWEN, ROLAND RUDD and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Nicholas Lyell was last night fighting growing pressure to quit as
attorney-general last night as Downing Street offered strong support and
Conservative MPs attacked Mr Michael Heseltine's evidence to the Scott
inquiry.
Some Tory backbenchers said Mr Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary,
had 'gone over the top' in accusing Sir Nicholas of giving contradictory
advice about his duty to sign public interest immunity certificates.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, demanded Sir Nicholas's
resignation during rowdy exchanges in the Commons over the government's
involvement in the Matrix Churchill case, which collapsed after the judge
accepted that the government had known about illegal arms deals.
Mrs Beckett said Sir Nicholas's position was becoming 'increasingly
untenable' as other ministers sought to 'save their own skins' by making him
the scapegoat for the collapse of the trial.
'What sticks in the throat of the British public is that having secretly
sold arms to Saddam Hussein which were used against British troops,
ministers were prepared to see innocent men go to jail to cover up their
conspiracy,' she said.
Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons, who was standing in for the prime
minister at question time, said Mr Heseltine had been advised 'quite
properly' by the attorney-general.
Downing Street also offered strong support to Sir Nicholas. He was said to
have the 'full confidence' of Mr John Major, the prime minister, who is on a
visit to the US.
But the government's attempt to rally support for Sir Nicholas was
undermined by Mr Major, who refused to comment until he had seen a
transcript of Mr Heseltine's evidence.
Conservative MPs said Sir Nicholas had been undermined by the evidence, but
was unlikely to be forced to resign before Lord Justice Scott reports in the
summer.
But there was also widespread support for Mr Heseltine's disclosure that he
resisted pressure to sign certificates because he feared that vital evidence
in the Matrix Churchill arms for Iraq trial would be suppressed.
Friends of Sir Nicholas said he was convinced he would be cleared by Lord
Justice Scott, and was determined to resist resignation unless he was
strongly criticised in the judge's final report.
Sir Nicholas is expected to mount a strong defence of his advice to Mr
Heseltine when he gives evidence to the inquiry on March 24.
Some ministers would like Sir Nicholas to appear earlier, in order to limit
the damage caused by Mr Heseltine's comments, but his appearance is unlikely
to be brought forward.
</TEXT>
