<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Argentina wins loan of Dollars 509m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The World Bank board yesterday approved a loan of Dollars 508.5m (Pounds
348.2m) for an innovative project to develop Argentina's capital markets.
The Washington-based development institution agreed to lend Dollars 500m for
a 'backstop' facility that will guarantee Argentina's commercial banks a
source of liquidity if interest rates rise in the future, and will thus
encourage them to lend money for longer periods to small and medium-sized
businesses.
The backstop fund will be owned by the Argentine government and managed by
an internationally recognised financial institution. It will undertake to
buy bonds from the commercial banks if interest rates rise beyond a fixed
level, to allow them to refinance loans made for periods longer than six
years.
The hope is that the facility will help strengthen the balance sheets of the
top 15 or 20 Argentine banks if interest rates turn upwards.
Argentina is one of the World Bank's biggest borrowers, with loans totalling
Dollars 3.6bn since the current government took office in 1989.
</TEXT>
