<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Australian budget priorities outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Australia's budget priorities in May would be 'to improve the prospects for
the long-term unemployed, to promote industry and regional development and
to implement the Native Title legislation', Mr Ralph Willis, Australian
treasurer, said yesterday.
These measures, coupled with the government's commitment to cut the budget
deficit to about 1 per cent of gross domestic product by 1996-97, meant
'little scope for further substantial initiatives this year'.
His comments came as he unveiled the government's initial budget platform,
contained in a 'fiscal framework' document. Publication is the starting
point for talks on budget details with the Labor party caucus and parties
holding the balance of power in the Senate. The government wants to avoid a
repeat of last year's fiasco when its finance package became stalled in
parliament. A defined period for negotiations has been set this year, and
the budget date moved forward to May.
The fiscal framework provided few new projections about the economy. But it
did play down the likelihood of a 'jobs levy' to fund the unemployment
measures. 'A jobs levy. . . has been suggested as a means of accommodating
increased expenditure pressure without prejudicing the deficit reduction
programme,' it said.
'The government ..would prefer to meet its aims without having to introduce
such a measure.'
</TEXT>
