<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Israel begins freeing prisoners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIRYAT ARBA, OCCUPIED WEST BANK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel began freeing 500 Palestinian prisoners yesterday, offered
compensation to Palestinian victims, and said up to 100 Jewish settlers
would be disarmed, as the government stepped up gestures to win back the PLO
to peace talks after last Friday's Hebron mosque massacre.
PLO leaders in the occupied territories said the gestures were insufficient,
but Israeli ministers said the Jewish state would not meet all PLO demands.
These include the disarmament of all 120,000 settlers and the dismantling of
some of the more extremist settlements such as Kiryat Arba, the 6,000-strong
Jewish community just outside Hebron where Dr Baruch Goldstein, who carried
out last Friday's massacre, lived.
Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, said Israel would prevent the
movement of extremist settlers into some sensitive areas, allow an unarmed
international force to be deployed in the West Bank and Gaza Strip for a
short period, and increase the Palestinian police force for Gaza-Jericho
from 8,000 to 10,000. But it rejected PLO demands for even tougher measures
against the settlers and settlements.
Palestinian leaders said Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, would have to stay
away from direct peace talks with Israel for at least two to four weeks, to
assuage outrage at the Hebron massacre.
As the prisoner release got under way, clashes erupted for a fourth day
throughout the occupied territories; Gen Ehud Barak, Chief of Staff, said
the army was expecting a wave of revenge attacks from Palestinians which it
could not prevent completely.
In Hebron and surrounding areas, a 24-hour curfew on Palestinians was
relaxed, but black flags of mourning remained on many homes. Relatives of
the victims of last Friday's bloodbath vowed to take revenge on Jewish
settlers.
</TEXT>
