<DOCNO>FT941-6467</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ECBDOAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940302
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Moscow taps new source of funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON, Agencies and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A decision by Moscow's mayor to introduce a new tax on the country's only
and fledgling currency market, in an effort to save the Russian capital's
treasury from ruin, has provoked angry protests from more than 100 Russian
banks.
The banks, shareholders and members of the Moscow inter-bank currency
exchange, said the 0.1 per cent tax on the volume of all deals would push
business away from Moscow to provincial currency markets.
The move would also be self-defeating, reducing overall tax revenues from
the exchange, and be a new burden on exporters, the banks said.
About Dollars 12.6bn, or a third of Russia's export earnings, were sold on
the exchange last year. The exchange, the country's first and the main venue
for central bank interventions to support the rouble, accounts for 80 per
cent of foreign exchange dealing in Russia.
However, Mayor Yuri Luzhkoz, was insisting yesterday that the city would
soon have no cash even for rubbish removal unless the government honoured
debts of tens of millions of dollars.
He told a municipality meeting that the government owed Rbs250bn to city
authorities but that the acting finance minister, Mr Sergei Dubinin, was
refusing to pay.
'The government has paid nothing to Moscow to help it function as the
capital of Russia. It hasn't given a single kopeck for the construction of
new metro lines. We might as well move the capital to somewhere else.'
Russia is in a chronic non-payments crisis as the government, state
enterprises, companies and individuals all owe each other money but no one
pays.
Amid this crisis, the finance ministry is trying to delay some payments as
it puts together a 1994 budget which is already stretched to cover trillions
of roubles promised by the government to ailing industries.
'The Russian leadership is like a gypsy who hasn't been feeding his horse
for a long time,' said Mr Luzhkov. 'It then decides the horse shouldn't be
fed at all. Finally the horse dies.'
Russia's gas company Gazprom said yesterday it would halt supplies to
Ukraine this week because payments had not been made. It also accused Kiev
of stealing gas from export pipelines crossing its territory, Reuter reports
from Moscow.
'We intend to cut off gas supplies from March 3 if Ukraine does not take any
steps,' said Gazprom's chief engineer, Mr Vladimir Podmarkov.
Ukraine, which is suffering acute fuel shortages, depends on Russia for most
of its oil and gas, but has been unable to pay for supplies.
In Kiev, a Ukrainian gas industry official doubted that Gazprom would carry
out its cut-off threat, which could lead to further tapping into export
pipelines by fuel-starved Ukrainian enterprises.
'Russia won't dare cut supplies completely,' said Mr Bohdan Babiy, chief
engineer at the transport division of the Ukrhazprom company. Previous
experience shows that our enterprises would just take the gas (meant) for
export (to western Europe) from the pipeline.'
Russia exported about 100bn cubic metres of gas outside the former Soviet
Union last year, mostly to Germany, Italy and France. More than 90 per cent
of these exports passed though Ukraine.
</TEXT>
