<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / US inflation fear hits markets: Unexpected increase in
economic expansion marred by sharp price rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, PATRICK HARVERSON and JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International bond and stock markets fell heavily yesterday after a closely
watched US economic index showed some sharp increases in manufacturing
costs.
At the same time, the US government reported that gross domestic product in
the final quarter of last year rose at a revised real annual rate of 7.5 per
cent, far above the 5.9 per cent preliminary estimate and the largest
quarterly expansion since the first three months of 1984.
The bond market, however, was far more influenced by the price data from the
National Association of Purchasing Managers monthly survey. Although its
composite index fell only slightly to 56.6 per cent from 57.7 per cent in
January, indicating continued healthy expansion, the association's price
index surged to 67 per cent from 59.8 per cent the previous month.
Renewed inflation fears left the US benchmark 30-year bond down more than 1
1/2 points by late afternoon, with the yield rising to 6.782 per cent. It
was the largest one-day decline in US bond prices for six months. European
bond markets fell sharply on the back of the US sell-off.
New York traders said investors were selling bonds because they believed any
sign of resurgent inflation would increase the likelihood of another
monetary policy tightening by the Federal Reserve. The US central bank last
tightened policy by pushing up short-term interest rates on February 4.
The selling in the bond market spread to the stock market, where investors
were equally perturbed by the prospect of another Fed rate rise. At one
stage the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down more than 40 points, but by
the close it had rallied to end down 22.79 at 3,809.23.
The setback in bond markets drove share prices lower in London in an
effective rerun of Thursday's rout. The FT-SE 100 Index closed at the lowest
point of the day, down 57.5 at 3,270.6. Trading volume in the stock market
remained fairly moderate, however, and the pressure again focused on stock
index futures.
Continental equity markets were also heavily marked down after the US
figures, with the CAC-40 index in Paris retreating more than 2 per cent and
the German Dax index of leading shares sliding 1 per cent during official
hours and another 2 per cent in after-hours trading.
The revised US GDP figures brought real annual growth to 3 per cent in 1993,
the best since the 3.9 per cent of 1988. More than half of the upward
revision was accounted for by exports, which grew at a 20.5 per cent annual
rate in the quarter and outstripped the recalculated 16.2 per cent expansion
in imports.
The overall thrust of the Purchasing Managers survey was also bullish. The
report noted that 'the strength in new orders strongly suggests future
continued growth, but very likely at a lower, more sustainable level'.
Increases in prices, it said, were 'primarily in products whose prices were
severely depressed', such as aluminium, brass, copper, nickel and zinc.
Of the component parts of the index, both new orders and the backlog in
orders grew in February, but at a lower rate than in January.
New export orders rose to the highest level in 4 1/2 years, while import
orders also grew, but at a lower rate than in plier deliveries were at the
highest level since June 1988, indicating strong demand from manufacturers.
The government's GDP report for the final quarter also showed broad-based
strength, together with low inflation.
