<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAR 94 / Car output at highest level for nearly 20 years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British car production last year reached its highest level since 1974, with
Rover moving further ahead of Ford as the UK's largest carmaker.
Rover's output of cars last year totalled 408,804, compared with Ford's
271,793, although the latter's total rises to 301,380 when Jaguar output is
included. In 1992, Rover produced 378,797 cars, compared with a combined
total of 322,946 cars from Ford and Jaguar.
Statistics from the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders show that the
UK's total car output last year reached 1.38m, nearly 7 per cent higher than
in 1992 and the highest since the 1.53m units reached in 1974.
However, this was in contrast to commercial vehicle output, which declined
further to the lowest level since 1958, mainly as a result of a steep drop
in demand in Continental Europe.
The figures emerged as Ford announced that short-time working had ended at
its Transit van plant at Southampton, and that output of Escorts from its
Halewood plant on Merseyside was being increased as a result of continuing
recovery in the UK vehicle market.
Ford produced 127,065 light commercial vehicles, compared with only 19,940
by Rover.
Total car output last year continued on its rising trend, up 6.47 per cent
to 1,375,524 units, the highest since 1974. This was in spite of lower
output at Vauxhall and Peugeot.
