<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / International Company News: Viacom lifted by rise in
European MTV subscribers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in the number of European subscribers to Viacom's MTV music
video network was behind an 11 per cent advance in operating earnings at the
US cable television group last year.
The company, which won a Dollars 10bn takeover battle for Paramount
Communications a fortnight ago, benefited from a 25 per cent fall in its
debt service costs, to Dollars 145m, and a reduction in its effective tax
rate to 43 per cent from 55 per cent.
These factors contributed to net income for the year of Dollars 158.2m or
Dollars 1.31 a share, up from Dollars 49m or 41 cents in 1992.
By the end of the year, MTV Europe had 58.3m subscribers, up from 43m, 12
months earlier. With other parts of the MTV Networks division, including
Nickleodeon, recording only modest gains in subscriber numbers, the European
performance largely accounted for the division's 27 per cent revenue
increase, to Dollars 677.9m from Dollars 533.4m. Operating earnings reached
Dollars 239.7m, up from Dollars 172.9m
Showtime, Viacom's other network operation, recorded a 5 per cent rise in
revenues, to Dollars 543.3m, while operating earnings slid to Dollars 32.3m
from Dollars 35.2m.
Earnings fell in the cable television division, due to new regulations on
rates charged to subscribers. Revenues rose 1 per cent to Dollars 416m,
while operating earnings fell 9 per cent to Dollars 110m.
For the final three months of the year, Viacom's net income was Dollars
13.6m or 11 cents a share, after a Dollars 12.8m dividend on convertible
stock issued to Nynex and Blockbuster Entertainment, which had backed the
Paramount bid.
This compared with net income of Dollars 11.6m or 10 cents a year before.
A number of Blockbuster shareholders yesterday asked the Delaware chancery
court for an injunction blocking the merger of the video rental company with
Viacom, which was agreed in principle in January.
The action is the latest sign of concern among some Blockbuster shareholders
that their company is being sold too cheaply. Viacom's shares have fallen
sharply in recent weeks, cutting into the value of its all-share offer.
Though the company's B shares yesterday rose Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 28 7/8
, they were trading at well below the Dollars 55 a share at which
Blockbuster agreed to buy a Dollars 1.25bn stake in January.
</TEXT>
