<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Active buying returned to stock index futures yesterday, encouraged by a
more favourable outlook on interest rates, a firm Wall Street and a positive
mood in UK gilts, writes Joel Kibazo.
The opening trade in the March contract on the FT-SE 100 was struck at a
firm 3,282 and the contract moved steadily forward, with most of the early
demand coming from US houses such as Salomon Brothers and Goldman Sachs. US
houses were among last week's big sellers.
A firm Wall Street boosted demand in the afternoon and March reached a peak
of 3,327, before coming off the top to finish at 3,319, a 3-point discount
to cash. Volume was a reduced 12,657 lots.
In the new FT-SE Mid 250 futures contract, March closed at 3,964 on volume
of 282 contracts, against last Friday's debut turnover of 617 lots. On the
rival OMLX, a mere 29 deals were registered in the same contract as it
finished at 3,966.
In traded options, total volume came to 32,212 contracts, of which 10,644
were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and 2,014 in the Euro FT-SE 100 option.
Lasmo was the most active stock option with 2,534 lots traded, followed by
Blue Circle with 1,525 and Lonrho at 1,467.
